{"id":"quant-ph/0207080","submitter":"Chiu Fan Lee","authors":"Chiu Fan Lee, Neil F. Johnson","title":"Exploiting Randomness in Quantum Information Processing","comments":"10 pages, final version","journal-ref":"Phys. Lett. A 301, 343 (2002)","doi":"10.1016/S0375-9601(02)01088-5","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We consider how randomness can be made to play a useful role in quantum\ninformation processing - in particular, for decoherence control and the\nimplementation of quantum algorithms. For a two-level system in which the\ndecoherence channel is non-dissipative, we show that decoherence suppression is\npossible if memory is present in the channel. Random switching between two\npotentially harmful noise sources can then provide a source of stochastic\ncontrol. Such random switching can also be used in an advantageous way for the\nimplementation of quantum algorithms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jul 2002 11:43:40 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 19 Aug 2002 13:59:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
